<DOC><DOCNO> AP880214-0031 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-14-88 1243EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Italy-Strike     02-14 0130</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Italy-Strike,0133</SECOND><HEAD>New Strike At Rome's Airport</HEAD><DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A strike by ground crew workers at Leonardo Da Vinciairport on Sunday forced cancellation of some of Alitalia'sdomestic and international flights.   Employees walked off the job at 7 a.m. and said they would stayout until midnight to protest the unexpected suspension ofnegotiations on a new contract.   Labor leaders representing ground crews and pilots told Italiannewspapers they will stage periodic strikes at Italian airportsuntil Feb. 29. Strikers want to force Alitalia, the national flagcarrier, to meet their demands for shorter hours and higher pay.   Travelers in Italy may face other transportation problems nearthe end of the month, when national train strikes are planned.Railroad workers plan strikes Feb. 26 and Feb. 28-29.</TEXT></DOC>